{{Italic title}}
[[File:Nishidhi stone with 14th century Old Kannada inscription from Tavanandi forest.JPG|thumb|alt=Nishidhi stone with 14th century old Kannada inscription from Tavanandi forest|''Nishidhi'', a 14th-century [[Hero stone|memorial stone]] depicting the observance of the vow of ''Sallekhana''  with old Kannada inscription. Found at Tavanandi forest, [[Karnataka]], India.]]
{{Jainism}}
'''''Sallekhana''''' ([[IAST]]: {{IAST|sallekhanā}}), also known as '''''Samlehna''''', '''''Santhara''''',  '''''Samadhi-marana''''' or '''''Sanyasana-marana''''';<ref name=":0" /> is a supplementary vow to the [[Ethics of Jainism|ethical code of conduct]] of [[Jainism]]. It is the religious practice of voluntarily fasting to death by gradually reducing the intake of food and liquids.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}} It is viewed in Jainism as the thinning of human passions and the body,{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=115}} and another means of destroying rebirth-influencing [[karma]] by withdrawing all physical and mental activities.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}} It is not considered as a suicide by Jain scholars because it is not an act of passion, nor does it deploy poisons or weapons.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}} After the ''sallekhana'' vow, the ritual preparation and practice can extend into years.<ref name=":0" />

''Sallekhana'' is a vow available to both for Jain [[Jain monasticism|ascetics]] and [[Śrāvaka (Jainism)|householders]].{{sfn|Battin|2015|p=47}} Historic evidence such as ''nishidhi'' engravings suggest ''sallekhana'' was observed by both men and women, including queens, in Jain history.<ref name=":0" /> However, in the modern era, death through ''sallekhana'' has been a relatively uncommon event.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=181}}

There is debate about the practice from a [[right to life]] and a [[freedom of religion]] viewpoint. In 2015, the [[Rajasthan High Court]] banned the practice, considering it [[suicide]]. Later that year, the [[Supreme Court of India]] stayed the decision of the Rajasthan High Court and lifted the ban on ''Sallekhana''.<ref name=Milind/>

==Vow==
{{See also|Ethics of Jainism}}

{{anchor|Mahavrata}}There are Five Great vows prescribed to followers of Jainism; ''[[Ahimsa in Jainism|Ahimsa]]'' (non-violence), ''[[Satya]]'' (not lying), ''[[Asteya]]'' (not stealing), ''[[Brahmacharya]]'' (chastity), and ''[[Aparigraha]]'' ([[non-possession]]).{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=4}} A further seven supplementary vows are also prescribed, which include three ''Gunavratas'' (merit vows) and four ''Shiksha vratas'' (disciplinary vows). The three ''Gunavratas'' are:  ''Digvrata'' (limited movements, limiting one's area of activity), ''Bhogopabhogaparimana'' (limiting use of consumable and non-consumable things), and ''Anartha-dandaviramana'' (abstain from purposeless sins). The ''Shikshavratas'' include: ''[[Samayika]]'' (vow to meditate and concentrate for limited periods), ''Desavrata'' (limiting movement and space of activity for limited periods), ''Prosadhopavāsa'' (fasting for limited periods), and ''Atithi-samvibhag'' (offering food to the ascetic).{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=87-91}}{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=5}}<ref>Pravin K. Shah, [http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~pluralsm/affiliates/jainism/jainedu/12vows.htm Twelve Vows of Layperson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511072328/http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~pluralsm/affiliates/jainism/jainedu/12vows.htm |date=11 May 2016 }}, Jainism Literature Center, Harvard University</ref>

''Sallekhana'' is treated as a supplementary to these twelve vows. However, some Jain teachers such as [[Kundakunda]], [[Devasena (Jain monk)|Devasena]], Padmanandin, and Vasunandin have included it under ''Shikshavratas''.{{sfn|Williams|1991|p=166}}

''Sallekhana'' ({{lang-sa|Sallikhita}}) means to properly 'thin out', 'scour out' or 'slender' the passions and the body through gradually abstaining from food and drink.{{sfn|Kakar|2014|p=174}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}} ''Sallekhana'' is divided into two components: ''Kashaya Sallekhana'' (slenderising of passions) or ''Abhayantra Sallekhana'' (internal slendering) and  ''Kaya Sallekhana'' (slenderising the body) or ''Bahya Sallekhana'' (external slendering).{{sfn|Settar|1989|p=113}} It is described as "facing death voluntarily through fasting".<ref name=":0" /> According to [[Jain texts]], ''Sallekhana'' leads to ''Ahimsa'' (non-violence or non-injury), as a person observing ''Sallekhana'' subjugates the passions, which are the root cause of ''Himsa'' (injury or violence).{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=116}}

==Conditions==
[[File:Sallekhana.pdf|thumb|alt=Sallekhana as expounded in the Jain text, Ratna Karanda Sravakachara|''Sallekhana'' as expounded in the Jain text, ''Ratnakaranda śrāvakācāra'']]
While ''Sallekhana'' is prescribed for both ''[[Śrāvaka (Jainism)|householders]]'' and [[Jain monasticism|ascetics]], Jain texts describe conditions when it is appropriate.<ref name=":0" />{{sfn|Wiley|2009|p=181}}{{sfn|Tukol|1976|pp=7–8}} It should not be observed by a householder without guidance of a Jain ascetic.{{sfn|Jaini|1998|p=231}}

Sallekhana is always voluntary, undertaken after public declaration, and never assisted with any chemicals or tools. The fasting causes thinning away of body by withdrawing by choice food and water to oneself. As death is imminent, the individual stops all food and water, with full knowledge of colleagues and spiritual counsellor.{{sfn|Jaini|2000|p=16}} In some cases, Jains with terminal illness undertake ''sallekhana'', and in these cases they ask for permission from their spiritual counsellor.{{sfn|Battin|2015|p=46}}{{refn|group=note|According to Somasundaram, ''Sallekhana'' is allowed in Jainism when normal religious life is not possible because of old age, extreme calamities, famine, incurable disease or when a person is nearing their death.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Somasundaram|first=Ottilingam|last2=Murthy|first2=AG Tejus|last3=Raghavan|first3=DVijaya|date=2016-10-01|title=Jainism – Its relevance to psychiatric practice; with special reference to the practice of Sallekhana|url=http://www.indianjpsychiatry.org/text.asp?2016/58/4/471/196702|journal=Indian Journal of Psychiatry|language=en|volume=58|issue=4|doi=10.4103/0019-5545.196702|pmc=5270277|pmid=28197009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228111528/http://www.indianjpsychiatry.org/text.asp?2016%2F58%2F4%2F471%2F196702|archivedate=28 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}} For a successful ''sallekhana'', the death must be with "pure means", voluntary, planned, undertaken with calmness, peace and joy where the person accepts to scour out the body and focuses his or her mind on spiritual matters.{{sfn|Battin|2015|p=47}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}}

''Sallekhana'' differs from other forms of ritual deaths recognized in Jainism as appropriate.{{sfn|Battin|2015|p=48}} The other situations consider ritual death to be better for a mendicant than breaking his or her [[#Mahavrata|Five Great vow]]s (''Mahavrata'').{{sfn|Battin|2015|p=48}} For example, celibacy is one of the Five vows, and ritual death is considered better than being raped or seduced or if the mendicant community would be defamed. A ritual death under these circumstances by consuming poison is believed to be better and allows for an auspicious rebirth.{{sfn|Battin|2015|p=48}}

==Procedure==
The duration of the practice can vary from a few days to years.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{citation |last=Mascarenhas |first=Anuradha |title=Doc firm on Santhara despite HC ban: I too want a beautiful death |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/doc-firm-on-santhara-despite-hc-ban-i-too-want-a-beautiful-death |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=25 August 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204114602/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/doc-firm-on-santhara-despite-hc-ban-i-too-want-a-beautiful-death/ |archivedate=4 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The sixth part of the ''Ratnakaranda śrāvakācāra'' describes ''Sallekhana'' and its procedure{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1917|pp=58–64}} as follows— {{quote|Giving up solid food by degrees, one should take to milk and whey, then giving them up, to hot or spiced water. 
[Subsequently] giving up hot water also, and observing fasting with full determination, he should give up his body, trying in every possible way to keep in mind the [[Namokar Mantra|pancha-namaskara mantra]].|Ratnakaranda śrāvakācāra (127–128){{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1917|pp=58–64}}}}

Jain texts mention five transgressions (''Atichara'') of the vow: the desire to be reborn as a human, the desire to be reborn as a divinity, the desire to continue living, the desire to die quickly, and the desire to live a sensual life in the next life. Other transgressions include: recollection of affection for friends, recollection of the pleasures enjoyed, and longing for the enjoyment of pleasures in the future.{{sfn|Williams|1991|p=170}}{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=10}}{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2011|p=111}}

{{anchor|three forms}}The ancient Svetambara Jain text ''[[Acharanga Sutra]]'', dated to about 3rd or 2nd century BCE, describes three forms of ''Sallekhana'': the ''Bhaktapratyakhyana'', the ''Ingita-marana,'' and the ''Padapopagamana''. In ''Bhaktapratyakhyana'', the person who wants to observe the vow selects an isolated place where he lies on a bed made of straw, does not move his limbs, and avoids food and drink until he dies. In ''Ingita-marana'', the person sleeps on bare ground. He can sit, stand, walk, or move, but avoids food until he dies. In ''Padapopagamana'', a person stands "like a tree" without food and drink until he dies.<ref name=":0" />

Another variation of ''Sallekhana'' is ''Itvara'' which consists of voluntarily restricting oneself in a limited space and then fasting to death.{{sfn|Battin|2015|p=48}}

==History==
[[File:Sallekhanā.jpg|thumb|alt=Sallekhana inscription at Shravanbelgola in the 7th century script|An inscription (No.130) in memory of Vinayadevasena who observed ''Sallekhana''. 7th century Kannada script. Found at [[Shravanbelgola]], Karnataka, India.]]
[[File:Doddahundi Nishidhi (memorial stone) with old Kannada inscription (869 C.E.).JPG|thumb|alt=Doddahundi Nishidhi (memorial stone) with old Kannada inscription (869 CE)|[[Doddahundi nishidhi inscription]] was raised in honor of [[Western Ganga Dynasty|Western Ganga]] King Nitimarga I in 869 CE who observed ''Sallekhana''.]]
[[File:KU14.jpg|thumb|alt=Sallekhana place for the monks at Udayagiri hills|The chamber for the ascetics to observe ''Sallekhana'' at [[Udayagiri and Khandagiri Caves|Udayagiri]] hills, [[Odisha]], India]]

===Textual===
The ''[[Acharanga Sutra]]'' ({{circa|5th century BCE|1st century BCE}}) describes [[#three forms|three forms]] of the practice. Early [[Svetambara]]{{refn|group=note|[[Svetambara]] and [[Digambara]] are two major sects of Jainism. See [[Jain schools and branches]].}} text ''Shravakaprajnapti'' notes that the practice is not limited to ascetics. The [[Vyākhyāprajñapti|Bhagavati Sūtra]] (2.1) also describes ''Sallekhana'' in great detail, as it was observed by Skanda Katyayana, an ascetic of [[Mahavira]]. The 4th century text ''[[Ratnakaranda śrāvakācāra]],'' and the Svetambara text ''Nava-pada-prakarana,'' also provide detailed descriptions. The ''Nava-pada-prakarana'' mentions seventeen methods of "voluntarily chosen death", of which it approves only three as consistent with the teachings of Jainism.{{sfn|Williams|1991|p=166}} The practice is also mentioned  in the 2nd century CE [[Sangam period|Sangam era]] poem ''Sirupanchamoolam''.<ref name=":1" />

The ''Panchashaka'' makes only a cursory mention of the practice and it is not described in ''Dharmabindu'' – both texts by [[Haribhadra]] ({{circa|5th century}}). In the 9th century text "[[Ādi purāṇa]]" by [[Jinasena]] the [[#three forms|three forms]] are described. ''Yashastilaka'' by [[Somadeva Suri|Somadeva]] (10th century) also describes the practice. Other writers like Vaddaradhane (10th century) and Lalitaghate also describe the ''Padapopagamana'', one of its forms. [[Hemchandra]] ({{circa|11th century}}) describes it in a short passage despite his detailed coverage of the observances of householders (''Shravakachara'').<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://isjs.in/sites/isjs.in/files/docs/Nishidhi%20Stones%20by%20A.%20Sundara.pdf|title=Nishidhi Stones and the ritual of Sallekhana|last=Sundara|first=A.|date=|website=International School for Jain Studies|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228111226/https://www.isjs.in/sites/isjs.in/files/docs/Nishidhi%20Stones%20by%20A.%20Sundara.pdf|archive-date=28 February 2018|dead-url=|access-date=21 April 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Williams|1991|p=166}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}}

According to ''[[Tattvartha Sutra]]'', "a householder willingly or voluntary adopts ''Sallekhana'' when death is very near."{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=10}} According to the medieval era Jain text, ''[[Puruşārthasiddhyupāya]]'', both the ascetics and the householder should "court voluntarily death at the end of life", thinking that only sallekhana is a pious death.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|pp=112–115}} The ''Silappadikaram'' (Epic of the Anklet) by the Jain prince-turned-monk, Ilango Adigal, mentions ''Sallekhana'' by the Jain nun, Kaundi Adigal.<ref name=":1" />

===Archeological===
In [[South India]], especially [[Karnataka]], a [[hero stone|memorial stone]] or footprint is erected to commemorate the death of person who observed ''Sallekhana''. This is known as ''Nishidhi'', ''Nishidige'' or ''Nishadiga''. The term is derived from the Sanskrit root ''Sid'' or ''Sad'' which means "to attain" or "waste away".<ref name=":0" />

These ''Nishidhis'' detail the names, dates, the duration of the vow, and other austerities performed by the person who observed the vow. The earliest ''Nishidhis'' (6th to 8th century) mostly have an inscription on the rock without any symbols. This style continued until the 10th century when footprints were added alongside the inscription. After the 11th century, ''Nishidhis'' are inscribed on slabs or pillars with panels and symbols. These slabs or pillars were frequently erected in ''[[mandapa]]''s (pillared pavilions), near ''[[basadi]]'' (temples), or sometimes as an inscription on the door frame or pillars of the temple.<ref name=":0" />

In [[Shravanabelgola]] in Karnataka, ninety-three ''Nishidhis'' are found ranging from circa 6th century to the 19th century. Fifty-four of them belong to the period circa 6th to the 8th century. It is believed that a large number of ''Nishidhis'' at Shravanabelgola follow the earlier tradition. Several inscriptions after 600 CE record that [[Chandragupta Maurya]] ({{circa|300 BCE}}) and his teacher [[Bhadrabahu]] observed the vow atop [[Chandragiri Hill]] at Sharavnabelagola. Historians such as [[Radha Kumud Mukherjee|R. K. Mookerji]] consider the accounts unproven, but plausible.{{sfn|Mookerji|1988|pp=39–41}}{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=19–20}}<ref>{{citation |last=Sebastian |first=Pradeep |title=The nun's tale |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-literaryreview/the-nuns-tale/article662328.ece |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=15 September 2010 |orig-year=1 November 2009 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114053258/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-literaryreview/the-nuns-tale/article662328.ece |archivedate=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Mallick |first=Anuradha |last2=Ganapathy |first2=Priya |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/468410/on-spiritual-quest.html |title=On a spiritual quest |date=29 March 2015 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924052938/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/468410/on-spiritual-quest.html |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

An undated [[Doddahundi nishidhi inscription|inscription]] in old [[Kannada script]] is found on the ''Nishidhi'' from Doddahundi near [[Tirumakudalu Narasipura]] in Karnataka. Historians such as [[John Faithfull Fleet|J. F. Fleet]], [[I. K. Sarma]], and E.P. Rice have dated it to 840 or 869 CE by its textual context.{{sfn|Rice|1982|p=13}} The memorial stone has a unique depiction in [[frieze]] of the ritual death (''Sallekhana'') of King Ereganga Nitimarga I ({{reign|853|869}}) of the [[Western Ganga Dynasty]]. It was raised by the king's son Satyavakya.{{sfn|Sarma|1992|p=17}}{{sfn|Sarma|1992|p=204}} In Shravanabelgola, the Kuge Brahmadeva pillar has a ''Nishidhi'' commemorating Marasimha, another Western Ganga king. An inscription on the pillar in front of Gandhavarna Basadi commemorates Indraraja, the grandson of the [[Rashtrakuta]] King Krishna III, who died in 982 after observing the vow.<ref name=":0" />

The inscriptions in South India suggest ''sallekhana'' was originally an ascetic practice which later extended to Jain householders. Its importance as an ideal death in the spiritual life of householders ceased by about the 12th century. The practice was revived in 1955 by the Digambara monk Acharya Santisagara.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}}

===Modern===
''Sallekhana'' is a respected practice in the [[Jain community]].{{sfn|Kakar|2014|p=173}} It has not been a "practical or general goal" among [[Svetambara]] Jains for many years. It was revived among [[Digambara monk]]s.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}} In 1955, Acharya [[Shantisagar]], a Digambara monk took the vow because of his inability to walk without help and his weak eye-sight.{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=98}}{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=100}}{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=104}} In 1999, Acharya [[Vidyanand]], another Digambara monk, took a twelve-year-long vow.{{sfn|Flügel|2006|p=353}}

Between 1800 and 1992, at least 37 instances of ''Sallekhana'' are recorded in Jain literature. There were 260 and 90 recorded Sallekhana deaths among Svetambara and Digambara Jains respectively between 1993 and 2003. According to Jitendra Shah, the Director of L D Institute of Indology in [[Ahmedabad]], an average of about 240 Jains practice ''Sallekhana'' each year in India. Most of them are not recorded or noticed.<ref name=iex>{{citation |url=http://www.expressindia.com/news/fullstory.php?newsid=74730 |title='Over 200 Jains embrace death every year' |work=Express India |date=30 September 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714055021/http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/news/fullstory.php?newsid=74730|archive-date=14 July 2015}}</ref> Statistically, ''Sallekhana'' is undertaken both by men and women of all economic classes and among the educationally forward Jains. It is observed more often by women than men.{{sfn|Braun|2008|pp=913–924}}

== Legality and comparison with suicide ==
Jain texts make a clear distinction between the ''Sallekhana'' and suicide.{{sfn|Chapple|1993|p=102}} Its dualistic theology differentiates between soul and matter. Soul is reborn in the Jain belief based on accumulated karma, how one dies contributes to the karma accumulation, and a pious death reduces the negative karmic attachments.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=179–181}}{{sfn|Battin|2015|pp=46–48}}{{sfn|Pechilis|Raj|2013|p=90}} The preparation for ''sallekhana'' must begin early, much before the approach of death, and when death is imminent, the vow of ''Sallekhana'' is observed by progressively slenderising the body and the passions.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|pp=114–115}}

The comparison of ''Sallekhana'' with suicide is debated since the early time of Jainism. The early Buddhist Tamil epic ''Kundalakesi'' compared it to suicide. It is refuted in the contemporary Tamil Jain literature such as in ''Neelakesi''.<ref name=":1" />

Professor S. A. Jain cites differences between the motivations behind suicide and those behind Sallekhana to distinguish them:{{cquote
|It is argued that it is suicide, since there is voluntary severance of life etc. No, it is not suicide, as there is no passion. Without attachment etc, there is no passion in this undertaking. A person who kills himself by means of poison, weapon etc, swayed by attachment, aversion or infatuation, commits suicide. But he who practices holy death is free from desire, anger and delusion. Hence it is not suicide.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|pp=116–117}}}}

[[Champat Rai Jain]], a Jainist scholar wrote in 1934:

{{cquote|Soul is a simple substance and as such immortal. Death is for compounds  whose dissolution is termed disintegration and death when it has reference to a living organism, that is a compound of spirit and matter. By dying in the proper way will is developed, and it is a great asset for the future life of the soul, which, as a simple substance, will survive the bodily dissolution and death. The true idea of ''Sallekhana'' is only this that when death does appear at last one should know how to die, that is one should die like a man, not like a beast, bellowing and panting and making vain efforts to avoid the unavoidable.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1934|p=179}}}}

Modern era Indian activists have questioned this rationale, calling the voluntary choice of death as an evil similar to [[sati (practice)|sati]], and have attempted to legislate and judicially act against this religious custom.{{sfn|Battin|2015|pp=47–48}} Article 21 of the [[Constitution of India]], 1950, guarantees the [[right to life]] to all persons within the territory of India and its states. In ''Gian Kaur vs The State Of Punjab'', the state high court ruled, "... 'right to life' is a natural right embodied in Article 21 but suicide is an unnatural termination or extinction of life and, therefore, incompatible and inconsistent with the concept of right to life".<ref name="GK1">{{cite web | title=Smt. Gian Kaur vs The State Of Punjab on 21 March, 1996 | website=Indian Kanoon | url=https://indiankanoon.org/doc/217501/ | accessdate=24 April 2017 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307134654/https://indiankanoon.org/doc/217501/ | archivedate=7 March 2017 | df=dmy-all }}{{PD-notice}}</ref>

''Nikhil Soni vs Union of India'' (2006), a case filed in the [[Rajasthan High Court]], citing the ''[[Aruna Shanbaug case|Aruna Ramchandra Shanbaug vs Union Of India]]'' case related to [[Euthanasia in India|euthanasia]], and the ''Gian Kaur'' case, argued, "No person has a right to take his own life consciously, as the right to life does not include the right to end the life voluntarily." So the petitioner cited ''Sallekhana'' as a suicide and thus punishable under Section 309 (attempt to commit suicide).<ref name="NK2003">{{cite web | title=Nikhil Soni vs Union Of India & Ors. on 10 August, 2015 | website=Indian Kanoon | date=24 May 2003 | url=https://indiankanoon.org/doc/173301527/ | accessdate=24 April 2017 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228111528/https://indiankanoon.org/doc/173301527/ | archivedate=28 February 2018 | df=dmy-all }}{{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name="BBC"/> The case also extended to those who helped facilitate the deaths of individuals observing ''Sallekhana,'' finding they were culpable under Section 306 (abetment of suicide) with aiding and abetting an act of suicide. It was also argued that ''Sallekhana'' "serves as a means of coercing widows and elderly relatives into taking their own lives".{{sfn|Braun|2008|pp=913–924}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kumar |first1=Nandini K. |year=2006 |title=Bioethics activities in India |journal=Eastern Mediterranean Health Journal |volume=12 |issue=Suppl 1 |pages=S56–65 |pmid=17037690}}</ref> An attempt to commit suicide was a crime under [[Section 309 of the Indian Penal Code|Section 309]] of the [[Indian Penal Code]].<ref name=BBC>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/jainism/customs/fasting_1.shtml|title=Religions: Jainism: Fasting|date=2009-09-10|work=[[BBC]]|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707200636/http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/jainism/customs/fasting_1.shtml|archivedate=7 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In response, the Jain community argued that prohibiting the practice is a violation of their [[freedom of religion in India|freedom of religion]], a [[fundamental right]] guaranteed by Article 15 and Article 25 of the Constitution of India.<ref>[[s:Constitution of India/Part III|article 15 of India Constitution]]</ref><ref name="NK2003"/>{{sfn|Braun|2008|pp=913–924}} The book ''Sallekhana Is Not Suicide'' by former Justice [[T. K. Tukol]] was widely cited in the court<ref name="NK2003"/> which opined that "''Sallekhana'' as propounded in the Jaina scriptures is not suicide."{{sfn|Tukol|1976|p=Preface}}

The [[Rajasthan High Court]] stated that "[The Constitution] does not permit nor include under Article 21 the right to take one's own life, nor can it include the right to take life as an essential religious practice under Article 25 of the Constitution". It further added that it is not established that ''Sallekhana'' is an essential practise of Jainism  and therefore not covered by Article 25 (1). So the High Court banned the practice in August 2015 making it punishable under Sections 306 (abetment of suicide) and 309 (attempt to commit suicide).<ref name="IBNlive 2015">{{citation |last=Vashishtha |first=Swati |title=Rajasthan HC bans starvation ritual 'Santhara', says fasting unto death not essential tenet of Jainism |work=News 18 |date=10 August 2015 |url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/rajasthan-hc-bans-starvation-ritual-santhara-says-fasting-unto-death-not-essential-tenet-of-jainism-1035893.html |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011060852/http://www.news18.com/news/india/rajasthan-hc-bans-starvation-ritual-santhara-says-fasting-unto-death-not-essential-tenet-of-jainism-1035893.html |archivedate=11 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Members of the Jain community held nationwide protest marches against the ban on ''Sallekhana''.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{citation |agency=Indo Asian News Service |url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/jain-community-protests-ban-religious-fast-death-154804860.html |title=Jain community protests ban on religious fast to death |date=24 August 2015 |work=[[Yahoo News]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016011023/https://in.news.yahoo.com/jain-community-protests-ban-religious-fast-death-154804860.html |archivedate=16 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Ghatwai |first=Milind |last2=Singh |first2=Mahim Pratap |title=Jains protest against Santhara order |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/jains-protest-against-santhara-order |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=25 August 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826144823/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/jains-protest-against-santhara-order/ |archivedate=26 August 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |agency=[[Press Trust of India]] |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/silent-march-by-jains-against-rajasthan-high-court-order-on-santhara/articleshow/48652929.cms |title=Silent march by Jains against Rajasthan High Court order on 'Santhara' |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=24 August 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827025719/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/silent-march-by-jains-against-rajasthan-high-court-order-on-santhara/articleshow/48652929.cms |archivedate=27 August 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

Advocate Suhrith Parthasarathy criticised the judgement of the High Court and wrote, "''Sallekhana'' is not an exercise in trying to achieve an unnatural death, but is rather a practice intrinsic to a person's ethical choice to live with dignity until death." He also pointed out that the Supreme Court in the ''Gian Kaur'' case explicitly recognises the right to live with human dignity within the ambit of right to life. He further cited that the Supreme Court wrote in the said case, "[The right to life] may include the right of a dying man to also die with dignity when his life is ebbing out. But the right to die with dignity at the end of life is not to be confused or equated with the right to die an unnatural death curtailing the natural span of life."<ref>{{citation |last=Parthasarathy |first=Suhrith |title=The flawed reasoning in the Santhara ban |url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-flawed-reasoning-in-the-santhara-ban/article7572183.ece |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=24 August 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114053258/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-flawed-reasoning-in-the-santhara-ban/article7572183.ece |archivedate=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name="GK1"/>

On 31 August 2015, the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] admitted the petition by Akhil Bharat Varshiya Digambar Jain Parishad and granted leave. It stayed the decision of the High Court and lifted the ban on the practice.<ref name=Milind>{{citation |last=Ghatwai |first=Milind |title=The Jain religion and the right to die by Santhara |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/the-jain-religion-and-the-right-to-die-by-santhara |date=2 September 2015 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222075226/http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/the-jain-religion-and-the-right-to-die-by-santhara/ |archivedate=22 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Anand |first=Utkarsh |title=Supreme Court stays Rajasthan High Court order declaring 'Santhara' illegal |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/supreme-court-stays-rajasthan-high-court-order-on-santhara |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=1 September 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905144803/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/supreme-court-stays-rajasthan-high-court-order-on-santhara/ |archivedate=5 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |agency=[[Press Trust of India]] |title=SC allows Jains to fast unto death |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/498291/sc-allows-jains-fast-unto.html |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |date=31 August 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913031944/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/498291/sc-allows-jains-fast-unto.html |archivedate=13 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Rajagopal |first=Krishnadas |title=Supreme Court lifts stay on Santhara ritual of Jains |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-lifts-stay-on-santhara-ritual-of-jains/article7600851.ece |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 March 2016 |orig-year=1 September 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130095531/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-lifts-stay-on-santhara-ritual-of-jains/article7600851.ece |archivedate=30 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In April 2017, the Indian parliament decriminalised suicide by passing the Mental Healthcare Act, 2017.<ref name=":451">{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/mental-health-bill-decriminalising-suicide-passed-by-parliament/|title=Mental health bill decriminalising suicide passed by Parliament|date=2017-03-27|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-03-27|language=en-US|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327160250/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/mental-health-bill-decriminalising-suicide-passed-by-parliament/|archivedate=27 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2017/175248.pdf|title=THE MENTAL HEALTHCARE ACT, 2017|last=|first=|publisher=The Gazette of India|date=7 April 2017|isbn=|location=New Delhi|pages=|format=PDF|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421194814/http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2017/175248.pdf|archivedate=21 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

== In Hinduism and Buddhism ==
There are similar practices in other religions like [[Prayopavesa]] in [[Hinduism]],{{sfn|Timms|2016|p=167}} and [[Sokushinbutsu]] in [[Buddhism]].{{sfn|Hayes|2016|p=16}}

The ancient and medieval scholars of Indian religions discussed suicide, and a person's right to voluntarily choose death. Suicide is broadly disapproved and discouraged by Buddhist, Hindu and Jaina texts.{{sfn|Arvind Sharma|1988|p=102}}{{sfn|Olivelle|2011|p=208 footnote 7}} The ''[[Satapatha Brahmana]]'' of Hinduism, for example, in section 10.2.6 discusses the nature of cyclic life and rebirth, and concludes that "therefore, one should not depart before one's natural lifespan", states David Brick, an Indologist at the Yale University.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brick|first1=David|title=The Dharmasastric Debate on Widow Burning|journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society|date=April–June 2010|volume=130|issue=2|pages=203–223|jstor=23044515}}</ref> However, for those who have renounced the world ([[sannyasa|sannyasi]], sadhu, yati, bhikshu), the Indian texts discuss when ritual choice of death is appropriate and what means of voluntarily ending one's life are appropriate.{{sfn|Olivelle|2011|pp=207–229}} The ''[[Sannyasa Upanishads]]'', for example, discuss many methods of religious death, such as slowing then stopping consumption of foods and drinks to death (similar to ''sallekhana''), walking into a river and drowning, entering fire, path of the heroes, and the Great Journey.{{sfn|Olivelle|2011|pp=208–223}}{{refn|group=note|The heroic path is explained as dying in a [[Just war theory|just battle]] on the side of [[dharma]] (right, good), and equivalent. The Great Journey is walking north without eating till one dies of exhaustion.{{sfn|Olivelle|1992|pp=134 footnote 18}} A similar practise known as ''Vadakirutthal'' (literally facing north) was prevalent in [[Sangam period]] in Tamilnadu. It is mentioned in Tamil anthologies such as in ''Puranaanooru''.<ref name=":1" />}}

Scholars disagree whether "voluntary religious death" discussed in [[Indian religions]] is same as other forms of suicide.{{sfn|Olivelle|1992|pp=134 footnote 18}}{{sfn|Olivelle|1978|pp=19–44}}<ref>{{cite journal | last=Sprockhoff | first=Joachim Friedrich | title=Die Alten im alten Indien Ein Versuch nach brahmanischen Quellen | journal=Saeculum | publisher=Bohlau Verlag | volume=30 | issue=4 | year=1979 | language=German| doi=10.7788/saeculum.1979.30.4.374 | accessdate=}}</ref>

